          "body": "The psalm's wisdom-instruction reaches its pastoral climax in 94:12: *Blessed is the man whom You chasten, O Lord, and whom You teach out of Your law.* The beatitude is remarkable in its context. The community is under active oppression; people are being killed (94:6). Into that context, the psalmist declares that the person God corrects and instructs is *blessed* (*esher* — the same word used in Psalm 1:1). The chastening (*yasar*) of God is not punishment but covenant parenting — the discipline a father gives a child he intends to mature. Hebrews 12:5-11 draws the same logic: do not regard lightly the Lord's discipline, for He disciplines every son He receives. The psalmist's theological move is audacious: what looks like God's abandonment of His people (they are being crushed, 94:5) is reframed as His discipline, which produces relief from adversity (94:13) precisely because a pit is being prepared for the wicked. The believer's suffering and the wicked's judgment are two sides of the same divine curriculum."
