          "body": "At 94:16 the psalm shifts from communal instruction to first-person testimony, and the shift is jarring in the best sense. The rhetorical questions of 94:16 — *Who will stand up for me against evildoers? Who will take his stand for me against those who do wickedness?* — echo the communal lament but now locate the crisis in the psalmist's individual life. The answer is the psalm's most intimate verse: *If the Lord had not been my help, my soul would soon have dwelt in the abode of silence* (94:17). This is testimony from the far side of rescue. The psalmist nearly died — and God intervened. From that position, two additional confessions follow: when he said *my foot has slipped*, God's *chesed* held him up (94:18); and when his anxious thoughts multiplied within him, God's consolations (*tanchum* — comfort, the same root as 'Comforter') delighted his soul (94:19). These three moves — near-death, slipping foot, multiplying anxiety — are the daily geography of life under persecution. And for each, the psalmist names a specific divine provision: help, *chesed*, consolation. The personal testimony is not abstract; it is the doctrinal argument of 94:8-15 embodied in one man's experience."
